card.name: #20 Brainstorm about content to accompany the app

data.text:
@andrejciho Thanks for adding me. My first thought is using our directory (Thero.org) for when people are looking for resources, but I might be a little biased :). I have a comprehensive list of the directories out there and would love to share ones that I respect. The default directory to find therapists is psychologytoday.com, but like all directories currently out there you can't order the listings in any meaningful way. Also, they often focus only on one type of resource. Goodtherapy.org is another therapist directory and has better articles than psychologytoday in my opinion. The focus on having "higher quality" therapists on their directory, but they don't really vet them in a meaningful way.

Regarding mental health articles and video: We're working on a way to have therapists in our community submit articles and have an up and down vote feature like Reddit. The goal is to have an online peer review system for articles from therapists so the public sees only the ones that rise to the top and not the fluff pieces. Think front page of the therapist internet. This might be something we could collaborate on and might be able to elevate mental health literacy. 

Also, we want to make a suggested content feature that tags content based on the stages of change (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transtheoretical_model#Stages_of_change). This way you can present content that progressively moves people along the stages of change instead of sitting in their earlier stages of contemplation or preparation. I haven't seen this done before, but I think it has a huge potential to increase help-seeking behavior. 

These are my initial thoughts, but I would love to see how we can come up with something that can make it easy for people to take action and get the support when they do.

card.desc:
This tool is very simple in what it does but there are a few things we feel strongly it isn't. Similar to how Skype warns its users upon signup that it's not a suitable alternative to calling emergency services (911 or 112), this tool is not a replacement for reaching out to emergency services in case of mental health emergency.

Our score-watching users keeping in touch with their score-reporting friends are not a formal emergency plan and this tool does not aspire or promise to facilitate that.

As any technology, our tool has a risk of failure greater than 0% and as such it should not be relied on in emergency situations.

cards.desc:
The original use case was in a scenario of friend supporting a friend that has an ongoing mental health challenge. Since then it was expand to use cases of addiction, weight loss etc. There might be other scenarios that we could have listed on the site.

We will need content for the use cases. The website should have a landing page for each.
cards.name: #28 Write out use cases

cards.desc:
This tool is very simple in what it does but there are a few things we feel strongly it isn't. Similar to how Skype warns its users upon signup that it's not a suitable alternative to calling emergency services (911 or 112), this tool is not a replacement for reaching out to emergency services in case of mental health emergency.

Our score-watching users keeping in touch with their score-reporting friends are not a formal emergency plan and this tool does not aspire or promise to facilitate that.

As any technology, our tool has a risk of failure greater than 0% and as such it should not be relied on in emergency situations.
